1
00:00:03,676 --> 00:00:11,164
[SPEAKER_04]: Good evening, and welcome to Senate House at the University of Cambridge for 90 minutes of question, answer, and live debate.

2
00:00:11,544 --> 00:00:14,768
[SPEAKER_04]: We invited the leaders of seven parties to take part.

3
00:00:15,048 --> 00:00:15,849
[SPEAKER_04]: Some are here.

4
00:00:16,289 --> 00:00:18,572
[SPEAKER_04]: Others chose to send senior representatives.

5
00:00:19,052 --> 00:00:32,907
[SPEAKER_04]: Those here are Tim Farron, leader of the Liberal Democrats, the leader of the Labour Party, Jeremy Corbyn, Caroline Lucas, co-leader of the Green Party, the leader of Plaid Cymru, Leanne Wood,

6
00:00:33,173 --> 00:00:35,882
[SPEAKER_04]: For the Conservatives, the Home Secretary, Amber Rudd.

7
00:00:36,986 --> 00:00:38,732
[SPEAKER_04]: Paul Nuttall, the leader of UKIP.

8
00:00:39,756 --> 00:00:42,846
[SPEAKER_04]: And Angus Robertson, the deputy leader of the SNP.

9
00:00:51,601 --> 00:00:58,610
[SPEAKER_04]: Our audience was selected by a leading opinion polling company to ensure that they are representative of the country as a whole.

10
00:00:59,010 --> 00:01:00,332
[SPEAKER_04]: They support different parties.

11
00:01:00,853 --> 00:01:06,940
[SPEAKER_04]: Some are undecided voters and they are also equally split along the lines of last year's EU referendum.

12
00:01:07,321 --> 00:01:10,104
[SPEAKER_04]: Half voted to leave the EU and half to remain.

13
00:01:10,144 --> 00:01:17,153
[SPEAKER_04]: And if you'd like to join in the debate at home, you can do so on Twitter using the hashtag BBC debate.

14
00:01:18,061 --> 00:01:24,802
[SPEAKER_04]: We begin with opening statements from all seven politicians, the order of which was decided by the drawing of lots.

15
00:01:25,244 --> 00:01:28,594
[SPEAKER_04]: First, it's the leader of Plaid Cymru, Leanne Wood.

16
00:01:32,928 --> 00:01:37,015
[SPEAKER_11]: Theresa May called this election because she's taking you for granted.

17
00:01:37,756 --> 00:01:43,547
[SPEAKER_11]: She won't turn up to these debates because her campaign of soundbites is falling apart.

18
00:01:44,288 --> 00:01:51,240
[SPEAKER_11]: Unlike Theresa May, I'm not afraid to defend my policies, my principles, my values.

19
00:01:51,220 --> 00:01:55,027
[SPEAKER_11]: Plaid Cymru exists to defend and build up our country.

20
00:01:55,708 --> 00:02:03,361
[SPEAKER_11]: In Wales it is Plaid Cymru that stands for fairness and equality and everyone who chooses to call Wales home.

21
00:02:04,062 --> 00:02:06,526
[SPEAKER_11]: For a hundred years Wales has voted Labour.

22
00:02:06,546 --> 00:02:09,752
[SPEAKER_11]: It hasn't stopped Tory rule.

23
00:02:09,732 --> 00:02:15,637
[SPEAKER_11]: Labour in Wales have their own manifesto and they're airbrushing their leader out of their campaign.

24
00:02:16,558 --> 00:02:23,244
[SPEAKER_11]: When Plaid Cymru has tried to ban zero hours contracts and to stop the bedroom tax, Welsh Labour voted against us.

25
00:02:23,865 --> 00:02:26,667
[SPEAKER_11]: It's time we stop doing what we've always done.

26
00:02:27,308 --> 00:02:29,590
[SPEAKER_11]: Let's instead give Wales a voice.

27
00:02:30,291 --> 00:02:32,472
[SPEAKER_11]: Give Plaid Cymru a mandate.

28
00:02:32,853 --> 00:02:39,739
[SPEAKER_11]: Elect a strong team of Plaid Cymru MPs to fight for a successful future for Wales.

29
00:02:39,837 --> 00:02:43,240
[SPEAKER_04]: And our next opening statement is from Caroline Lucas of the Green Party.

30
00:02:44,362 --> 00:02:48,986
[SPEAKER_05]: On June the 8th, you can lay the foundations for a new kind of politics.

31
00:02:49,747 --> 00:02:51,829
[SPEAKER_05]: Your vote can change everything.

32
00:02:52,750 --> 00:02:59,396
[SPEAKER_05]: Imagine this, a country that leads the world in clean energy, not fracks its way to climate chaos.

33
00:03:00,217 --> 00:03:05,963
[SPEAKER_05]: A country that spends its money on hospitals and schools, not nuclear bombs.

34
00:03:05,943 --> 00:03:09,958
[SPEAKER_05]: A country that welcomes child refugees, not blocks them at the border.

35
00:03:10,801 --> 00:03:14,856
[SPEAKER_05]: A country that's open to its neighbours, not isolated from them.

36
00:03:15,072 --> 00:03:17,877
[SPEAKER_05]: A country that celebrates diversity, not fears it.

37
00:03:18,678 --> 00:03:24,387
[SPEAKER_05]: A country that's friends with the good guys, not the climate criminals and the dodgy dictators.

38
00:03:25,269 --> 00:03:29,556
[SPEAKER_05]: A country that cares for those with dementia, not one that taxes them.

39
00:03:30,337 --> 00:03:36,207
[SPEAKER_05]: We've shown time and again, you don't need the keys to number 10 to open the door to change.

40
00:03:37,008 --> 00:03:40,354
[SPEAKER_05]: On June the 8th, let's unlock that door together.

41
00:03:40,334 --> 00:03:43,358
[SPEAKER_05]: Fearless Green MPs in opposition to the Tories.

42
00:03:43,939 --> 00:03:47,344
[SPEAKER_05]: Independent Green MPs holding Labour's feet to the fire.

43
00:03:48,045 --> 00:03:52,070
[SPEAKER_05]: Pioneering Green MPs to make our economy fit for tomorrow.

44
00:03:53,071 --> 00:03:55,354
[SPEAKER_05]: We decide the future by what we do now.

45
00:03:56,035 --> 00:03:59,160
[SPEAKER_04]: Vote Green on June 8th.

46
00:03:59,180 --> 00:04:03,085
[SPEAKER_04]: And the next of our opening statements is for the Conservatives from Amber Rudd.

47
00:04:04,043 --> 00:04:09,750
[SPEAKER_06]: In eight days, you have a vital choice to make about who you want to lead the country.

48
00:04:10,491 --> 00:04:12,293
[SPEAKER_06]: Do you want Theresa May and her team?

49
00:04:13,074 --> 00:04:22,986
[SPEAKER_06]: A team that has a plan, and it's one that doesn't duck the hard choices about living within our means, but is also a plan that will build on the success we have delivered.

50
00:04:23,426 --> 00:04:30,034
[SPEAKER_06]: Success in cutting the deficit, stabilising the economy, getting more people into employment.

51
00:04:30,014 --> 00:04:33,638
[SPEAKER_06]: It will build on our commitment to having a country that works for everyone.

52
00:04:34,699 --> 00:04:42,486
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, there are seven of us here tonight, and I'm sure you will hear plenty of bluff, bravado, and tempty, shiny election promises.

53
00:04:43,727 --> 00:04:49,954
[SPEAKER_06]: But the only question to consider is who should be in number 10 to steer Britain to a brighter future.

54
00:04:50,634 --> 00:04:56,460
[SPEAKER_06]: Jeremy Corbyn, with his money tree wish list manifesto and no plan for Brexit,

55
00:04:56,795 --> 00:05:07,656
[SPEAKER_06]: or Theresa May and her record of delivery with her clear plan for Brexit and the strong team behind her who can make sure the country gets to that brighter future.

56
00:05:09,119 --> 00:05:11,023
[SPEAKER_06]: And next, it's Jeremy Corbyn.

57
00:05:11,780 --> 00:05:15,446
[SPEAKER_14]: Tonight I am here to debate the future of our country.

58
00:05:16,108 --> 00:05:20,635
[SPEAKER_14]: The question in this election is whether we want a country for the many or just a few.

59
00:05:20,696 --> 00:05:31,915
[SPEAKER_14]: The state of our NHS, our children's schools, social care for older people, our young people saddled with debt, none of that is remotely strong or stable.

60
00:05:31,895 --> 00:05:39,787
[SPEAKER_14]: And now the Conservatives want five more years of cuts to our vital public services to fund tax handouts for the wealthy few.

61
00:05:40,267 --> 00:05:42,511
[SPEAKER_14]: Labour will make very different choices.

62
00:05:42,811 --> 00:05:46,336
[SPEAKER_14]: There will be no tax rises for 95% of taxpayers.

63
00:05:46,637 --> 00:05:54,088
[SPEAKER_14]: But we will ask those with the most to contribute a bit more so no one is held back from achieving their potential.

64
00:05:54,068 --> 00:05:56,174
[SPEAKER_14]: On June the 8th, you have a choice.

65
00:05:56,194 --> 00:06:03,555
[SPEAKER_14]: More cuts in services and living standards with the Conservatives or vote Labour to transform Britain for the many, not the few.

66
00:06:04,295 --> 00:06:06,438
[SPEAKER_04]: And now the UKIP leader, Paul Nuttall.

67
00:06:06,839 --> 00:06:22,904
[SPEAKER_12]: UKIP will always put the interests of British people first, whether that is prioritising our NHS and social care over a bloated and ineffective foreign aid programme, or protecting those who are most at risk from wage compression because of unskilled mass immigration.

68
00:06:23,425 --> 00:06:30,336
[SPEAKER_12]: UKIP will always stand up for those who have been let down and left behind by the Westminster elites.

69
00:06:30,316 --> 00:06:34,600
[SPEAKER_12]: A government's job, first and foremost, is to protect the public.

70
00:06:35,141 --> 00:06:44,770
[SPEAKER_12]: Our police, our intelligence services, our armed forces and our border force must be given the tools and the resources they need to do their jobs effectively.

71
00:06:45,331 --> 00:06:46,572
[SPEAKER_12]: But money isn't everything.

72
00:06:46,592 --> 00:06:49,375
[SPEAKER_12]: Politicians must show leadership.

73
00:06:49,835 --> 00:06:57,403
[SPEAKER_12]: They must, without fear or favour, ensure that our way of life, our values and our democracy is secure.

74
00:06:57,383 --> 00:06:58,807
[SPEAKER_12]: I believe in our great country.

75
00:06:59,329 --> 00:07:00,652
[SPEAKER_12]: I believe in British values.

76
00:07:01,074 --> 00:07:02,297
[SPEAKER_12]: I believe in our way of life.

77
00:07:02,658 --> 00:07:06,930
[SPEAKER_12]: And as you will see tonight, UKIP believes in Britain.

78
00:07:06,950 --> 00:07:09,317
[SPEAKER_04]: The SNP opening statement from Angus Robertson.

79
00:07:09,652 --> 00:07:10,073
[SPEAKER_13]: Good evening.

80
00:07:10,754 --> 00:07:13,418
[SPEAKER_13]: This election is about the kind of country we want to be.

81
00:07:13,959 --> 00:07:18,607
[SPEAKER_13]: Now, more than ever, Scotland needs strong SNP voices at Westminster.

82
00:07:19,188 --> 00:07:24,116
[SPEAKER_13]: And SNP MPs will work with others to promote fairness across all of the UK.

83
00:07:24,817 --> 00:07:28,183
[SPEAKER_13]: A vote for the SNP is a vote against Tory cuts.

84
00:07:28,163 --> 00:07:33,055
[SPEAKER_13]: that will harm our public services and push many more hard-working families into poverty.

85
00:07:33,837 --> 00:07:39,872
[SPEAKER_13]: It's a vote for jobs and against an extreme Brexit, which will put jobs and living standards at risk.

86
00:07:40,674 --> 00:07:45,987
[SPEAKER_13]: It's a vote to reinforce the right of the people of Scotland to decide their own future.

87
00:07:45,967 --> 00:07:51,575
[SPEAKER_13]: We can't afford a Tory government which thinks it can do anything it likes without being held to account.

88
00:07:52,276 --> 00:07:57,844
[SPEAKER_13]: And we can't give Theresa May a blank cheque to pursue any kind of Brexit, no matter the cost.

89
00:07:58,725 --> 00:08:03,031
[SPEAKER_13]: In Scotland, the SNP is the only party strong enough to stand up to the Tories.

90
00:08:03,752 --> 00:08:06,997
[SPEAKER_13]: So vote SNP for a strong voice for Scotland at Westminster.

91
00:08:07,578 --> 00:08:10,041
[SPEAKER_13]: That voice is needed now more than ever.

92
00:08:11,163 --> 00:08:15,028
[SPEAKER_04]: And for our final opening statement, the leader of the Liberal Democrats, Tim Farron.

93
00:08:16,308 --> 00:08:17,932
[SPEAKER_16]: Where do you think Theresa May is tonight?

94
00:08:18,493 --> 00:08:19,535
[SPEAKER_16]: Take a look out your window.

95
00:08:19,936 --> 00:08:22,722
[SPEAKER_16]: She might be out there sizing up your house to pay for your social care.

96
00:08:23,685 --> 00:08:26,150
[SPEAKER_16]: And why do you think she called this election?

97
00:08:26,170 --> 00:08:32,865
[SPEAKER_16]: She wants five years as prime minister, and she thinks you'll give it to her, no questions asked, literally.

98
00:08:32,845 --> 00:08:39,315
[SPEAKER_16]: even if she brings in a dementia tax, sacks your kids' teachers and nicks their lunches while she's at it.

99
00:08:39,756 --> 00:08:42,460
[SPEAKER_16]: We can all agree that is a rubbish offer.

100
00:08:42,741 --> 00:08:49,973
[SPEAKER_16]: Look, I know we don't all agree on Brexit, but she's off to negotiate a deal for you, for me, for all of us.

101
00:08:50,554 --> 00:08:52,356
[SPEAKER_16]: Imagine if it's a bad deal.

102
00:08:52,797 --> 00:08:54,460
[SPEAKER_16]: I mean, dementia tax bad.

103
00:08:55,121 --> 00:08:57,705
[SPEAKER_16]: I know that to persuade you to vote Liberal Democrat

104
00:08:57,685 --> 00:09:00,208
[SPEAKER_16]: I have to give you some really good reasons.

105
00:09:00,428 --> 00:09:01,029
[SPEAKER_16]: So here's three.

106
00:09:01,529 --> 00:09:06,054
[SPEAKER_16]: One, I'll rescue the NHS and social care by putting a penny on income tax.

107
00:09:06,415 --> 00:09:10,559
[SPEAKER_16]: Two, I'll give you the final say on the Brexit deal, not Theresa May.

108
00:09:10,880 --> 00:09:16,486
[SPEAKER_16]: Three, whatever power you give me, I'll use it to stop her taking you for granted.

109
00:09:16,546 --> 00:09:19,930
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you all for those opening statements.

110
00:09:29,545 --> 00:09:33,691
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's go straight to our first question, and it comes from Nicola Collins.

111
00:09:34,732 --> 00:09:35,574
[SPEAKER_08]: I work.

112
00:09:35,594 --> 00:09:36,735
[SPEAKER_08]: I pay my taxes.

113
00:09:37,156 --> 00:09:38,878
[SPEAKER_08]: I haven't had a pay rise in years.

114
00:09:39,459 --> 00:09:41,923
[SPEAKER_08]: I live alone and see all my bills going up.

115
00:09:42,604 --> 00:09:45,288
[SPEAKER_08]: Working people are the backbone of this country.

116
00:09:45,728 --> 00:09:47,991
[SPEAKER_08]: How are you going to help people like me?

117
00:09:49,273 --> 00:09:51,216
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Nicola.

118
00:09:51,652 --> 00:09:54,978
[SPEAKER_04]: Amber Rudd, your party's presided over this squeeze in living standards.

119
00:09:55,559 --> 00:09:57,703
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, thank you Nicola for the question.

120
00:09:58,365 --> 00:10:05,939
[SPEAKER_06]: My party has presided over making sure that people on lower wages are able to keep more of the wages they earn.

121
00:10:05,959 --> 00:10:07,862
[SPEAKER_06]: We must take it within context.

122
00:10:08,303 --> 00:10:14,655
[SPEAKER_06]: Since 2009 we had, up from the run to 2009, we had one of the largest peacetime recessions.

123
00:10:14,635 --> 00:10:17,399
[SPEAKER_06]: and we've managed to rebuild the economy since then.

124
00:10:17,920 --> 00:10:33,224
[SPEAKER_06]: But my party is focused on making sure that we help people like Nicola, which is why we're going to continue to take people out of taxes, making sure that the amount you can earn before you have to pay tax rises to £12,500 and we're going to live within our means.

125
00:10:33,244 --> 00:10:37,470
[SPEAKER_06]: Some of the offers you will hear tonight are just fanciful.

126
00:10:37,450 --> 00:10:43,281
[SPEAKER_06]: In order to have a strong economy, to support Nicola and others, we need to make sure we have that strong economy.

127
00:10:43,601 --> 00:10:50,414
[SPEAKER_06]: And the way to make sure that we have it is to have a strong negotiating position as we go into leaving the European Union.

128
00:10:50,574 --> 00:10:58,048
[SPEAKER_06]: You're going to hear me say that a lot tonight because the worst outcome would be if we're not able to negotiate a strong deal with the European Union.

129
00:10:58,068 --> 00:10:59,651
[SPEAKER_04]: The question is on living standards.

130
00:10:59,771 --> 00:11:00,673
[SPEAKER_04]: Jeremy Corbyn.

131
00:11:01,143 --> 00:11:09,777
[SPEAKER_14]: Living standards have fallen in the past seven years under the coalition government with the Liberal Democrats and the Tories and now under the Tory government itself.

132
00:11:10,298 --> 00:11:13,063
[SPEAKER_14]: Six million people are earning less than the living wage.

133
00:11:13,403 --> 00:11:15,587
[SPEAKER_14]: A million are on zero-hours contracts.

134
00:11:15,607 --> 00:11:21,196
[SPEAKER_14]: Public sector workers have had a pay cut of at least 14% over the past seven years.

135
00:11:21,557 --> 00:11:23,961
[SPEAKER_14]: We will lift the pay cap on the public sector.

136
00:11:24,201 --> 00:11:27,066
[SPEAKER_14]: We will introduce a living wage of £10 an hour

137
00:11:27,046 --> 00:11:35,475
[SPEAKER_14]: by 2020 and we won't punish workers who want to take their rights to a tribunal where they have to pay charges and fees.

138
00:11:35,735 --> 00:11:36,636
[SPEAKER_14]: We will abolish that.

139
00:11:37,117 --> 00:11:42,883
[SPEAKER_14]: Our determination is that those who produce the wealth of this country should benefit from the wealth of this country.

140
00:11:43,103 --> 00:11:48,248
[SPEAKER_14]: What we've seen is a massive gap growing between those at work and those at the top.

141
00:11:48,268 --> 00:11:53,154
[SPEAKER_14]: It's times 186 between those on the shop floor and those in the boardroom.

142
00:11:53,174 --> 00:11:55,416
[SPEAKER_14]: That has to change and we will ensure it does.

143
00:11:55,683 --> 00:11:58,447
[SPEAKER_04]: Angus Robertson, how would you help working people like Nicola?

144
00:11:59,128 --> 00:12:04,236
[SPEAKER_13]: Well, the first thing I would say is that governments have choices about the kind of economic policy they pursue.

145
00:12:04,336 --> 00:12:15,333
[SPEAKER_13]: And the Tories now alone in government and previously working with the Liberal Democrats introduced austerity measures which are hitting those in society with the lowest incomes the most.

146
00:12:16,054 --> 00:12:19,800
[SPEAKER_13]: And frankly, I think the time has come for that to end.

147
00:12:19,780 --> 00:12:22,184
[SPEAKER_13]: And politicians can make different choices.

148
00:12:22,765 --> 00:12:29,074
[SPEAKER_13]: And every SNP MP elected to Westminster will stand up for those different choices and an end to austerity.

149
00:12:30,156 --> 00:12:31,097
[SPEAKER_13]: It is about choices.

150
00:12:31,598 --> 00:12:35,204
[SPEAKER_13]: The Tories have chosen to support those who are wealthiest in society.

151
00:12:35,724 --> 00:12:36,466
[SPEAKER_13]: We don't agree with them.

152
00:12:36,966 --> 00:12:39,510
[SPEAKER_13]: We think those who have the most should pay a little bit more.

153
00:12:39,951 --> 00:12:46,581
[SPEAKER_13]: And that's why we're in favour of the highest earners seeing their taxes rising from 45 to 50p.

154
00:12:46,730 --> 00:12:53,976
[SPEAKER_13]: We're also incidentally, also supportive of looking at changes to the pay restraint that we've seen through these times of austerity.

155
00:12:54,357 --> 00:12:56,999
[SPEAKER_13]: That's going to happen in Scotland under an SNP government.

156
00:12:57,399 --> 00:13:00,782
[SPEAKER_13]: We will press the UK government to do the same in the rest of the UK.

157
00:13:01,563 --> 00:13:02,804
[SPEAKER_13]: Lastly, I want to make this point.

158
00:13:03,304 --> 00:13:09,290
[SPEAKER_13]: Some of those people on the lowest incomes have been massively hit by welfare cuts.

159
00:13:09,310 --> 00:13:15,555
[SPEAKER_13]: And I think the time has come to end punishing disabled people, end a bedroom tax,

160
00:13:20,092 --> 00:13:24,541
[SPEAKER_13]: and leaving people with the lowest incomes with too little to pay for the essentials.

161
00:13:25,202 --> 00:13:27,767
[SPEAKER_06]: That changes about political changes.

162
00:13:27,887 --> 00:13:39,349
[SPEAKER_06]: On the direct point of payments to help people who are disabled, we are a party who will always support those in most need and the Welfare Bill for helping people on disabilities

163
00:13:39,329 --> 00:13:43,513
[SPEAKER_06]: has gone up 7 billion in the past seven years and is now at 50 billion.

164
00:13:43,533 --> 00:13:46,535
[SPEAKER_06]: We will always provide that safety net where it's needed.

165
00:13:46,636 --> 00:13:53,722
[SPEAKER_14]: Amber, you've tried to take personal independence payments away from people with disabilities and then you turned yourselves around in a few days on that.

166
00:13:53,742 --> 00:13:55,063
[SPEAKER_14]: You're not credible on this issue.

167
00:13:55,083 --> 00:14:09,336
[SPEAKER_06]: Jeremy, I know there is no extra payment you don't want to add to, no tax you don't want to rise, but the fact is we have to concentrate our resources on the people who need it most and we have to stop thinking, as you do, that there's a magic money tree.

168
00:14:09,316 --> 00:14:12,805
[SPEAKER_06]: You have to be accountable for the money you want to spend.

169
00:14:13,206 --> 00:14:14,690
[SPEAKER_04]: I'd like to bring in some of the other parties.

170
00:14:14,750 --> 00:14:19,222
[SPEAKER_04]: Tim Farron, you've argued for this election being about providing a good and credible opposition.

171
00:14:19,623 --> 00:14:24,355
[SPEAKER_04]: Which of these parties do you think has the right economic formula for living standards?

172
00:14:24,335 --> 00:14:27,299
[SPEAKER_16]: I mean, to answer Nicola's question, I mean, economics is about people.

173
00:14:27,619 --> 00:14:28,680
[SPEAKER_16]: It's not about figures.

174
00:14:28,700 --> 00:14:33,927
[SPEAKER_16]: It's about people's experience and how they can afford to feed their children and look after them.

175
00:14:35,328 --> 00:14:40,134
[SPEAKER_16]: Like many people, I have known in my life what it's like to not be able to pay the bills.

176
00:14:40,415 --> 00:14:45,641
[SPEAKER_16]: It matters to me that we build a country for all of our children where people are decent to one another.

177
00:14:45,941 --> 00:14:48,304
[SPEAKER_16]: A strong welfare state is essential.

178
00:14:48,364 --> 00:14:53,751
[SPEAKER_16]: I've been helping two people in my constituency with their PIP payments in the last month.

179
00:14:53,731 --> 00:14:58,220
[SPEAKER_16]: both of whom were chief executives of different companies in the not-too-distant past.

180
00:14:58,240 --> 00:15:07,538
