00:41:43,100 --> 00:41:47,365
[SPEAKER_14]: Why should a child's future be determined by the postcode in which they're born?

537
00:41:47,666 --> 00:42:03,925
[SPEAKER_14]: That's why we are determined to bring in free preschool 30 hours a week from two to four-year-olds and make sure that every primary school child gets a free lunch every day so they can learn while they're properly fed.

538
00:42:03,945 --> 00:42:04,686
[SPEAKER_11]: Jeremy, you have a Labour government.

539
00:42:04,666 --> 00:42:06,928
[SPEAKER_11]: in Wales and they aren't doing those things.

540
00:42:07,229 --> 00:42:11,273
[SPEAKER_11]: You have a Labour government in Wales that is charging students to go to university.

541
00:42:11,833 --> 00:42:15,897
[SPEAKER_11]: Why are you saying this here when you have an example of a Labour government and it's not doing that?

542
00:42:15,917 --> 00:42:18,019
[SPEAKER_14]: This is a UK government and a UK government policy.

543
00:42:18,039 --> 00:42:20,402
[SPEAKER_11]: Are the Labour's different in UK and different in Wales?

544
00:42:20,602 --> 00:42:31,753
[SPEAKER_14]: It's going to be a UK policy and it will mean that the money is made available there by increasing tax, not for the first 95% of the population, but

545
00:42:31,970 --> 00:42:35,015
[SPEAKER_14]: the other 5% to ensure the funds are there.

546
00:42:35,035 --> 00:42:47,598
[SPEAKER_14]: Because I am fed up with the idea that so many children growing up in poorer households and poorer communities don't get the same chances as others to get to university and get on in life.

547
00:42:47,738 --> 00:42:56,273
[SPEAKER_14]: They lose and we all lose because we lose those skilled, brilliant people that want to contribute to our community.

548
00:42:56,253 --> 00:43:04,120
[SPEAKER_04]: Your manifesto also included major spending promises, an extra £180 billion for public services, UK-wide?

549
00:43:04,480 --> 00:43:06,522
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes, it's actually £128 billion.

550
00:43:06,542 --> 00:43:17,692
[SPEAKER_13]: The different sources are rescheduling the UK's finances and £10 billion, that's £118 billion and £10 billion in funds to be raised through taxation, largely through the £0.45 to £0.50 tax raise change.

551
00:43:17,712 --> 00:43:22,657
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm just interested by Jeremy, following SNP policy and tuition fees, I'd like to congratulate you, Jeremy.

552
00:43:22,677 --> 00:43:26,260
[SPEAKER_13]: It's a shame your party north of the border has opposed the SNP.

553
00:43:26,240 --> 00:43:37,033
[SPEAKER_13]: Can I bring up a really serious issue, which I think has been the biggest so far in the campaign, and that relates to social care and to pensions.

554
00:43:37,854 --> 00:43:50,830
[SPEAKER_13]: And I think when older people are facing the most likely prospect, which is a re-elected Tory government, sadly, and they are promising a dementia tax, an end to the winter fuel payment,

555
00:43:51,468 --> 00:43:56,979
[SPEAKER_13]: and cuts to the pension, I think those people deserve to know by how much.

556
00:43:57,840 --> 00:43:59,223
[SPEAKER_13]: And they haven't been told.

557
00:43:59,684 --> 00:44:04,954
[SPEAKER_13]: Now the Prime Minister didn't have the guts to come along this evening to tell us, so I'd like to challenge...

558
00:44:07,347 --> 00:44:15,158
[SPEAKER_13]: I would like to challenge Amber Rudd to tell us the answer to that question now because they must have costed it.

559
00:44:15,539 --> 00:44:17,482
[SPEAKER_13]: They must know how much money that will bring in.

560
00:44:17,842 --> 00:44:24,552
[SPEAKER_13]: Please tell the pensioners of this country how much they will have to pay to fund Tory austerity.

561
00:44:24,632 --> 00:44:25,153
[SPEAKER_13]: How much?

562
00:44:25,133 --> 00:44:27,299
[SPEAKER_06]: OK, don't give up on me quite yet, Angus.

563
00:44:27,319 --> 00:44:29,204
[SPEAKER_06]: It's only halfway through the debate.

564
00:44:29,344 --> 00:44:34,498
[SPEAKER_06]: Theresa may not be here, but I hope to make a good fist of setting out the Conservative Party policy.

565
00:44:35,200 --> 00:44:40,273
[SPEAKER_06]: We've made a clear decision to make sure that we protect the poorest in our society.

566
00:44:40,253 --> 00:44:48,249
[SPEAKER_06]: Which means that the pensioners will be protected, that winter fuel payment won't be paid to millionaires.

567
00:44:48,389 --> 00:44:50,874
[SPEAKER_06]: No, it'll be focused.

568
00:44:50,914 --> 00:44:54,841
[SPEAKER_06]: So where will the levels be put then?

569
00:44:54,921 --> 00:44:57,807
[SPEAKER_06]: Where will the levels be put?

570
00:44:57,787 --> 00:45:03,233
[SPEAKER_06]: Under a Labour government, the pensioners saw a rise in their pensions of 85p in one year.

571
00:45:03,694 --> 00:45:07,798
[SPEAKER_06]: Under this government, we've seen pensioners' pay rise by over £1,000.

572
00:45:07,958 --> 00:45:10,802
[SPEAKER_14]: Can you now admit that you're protecting the triple lock?

573
00:45:10,882 --> 00:45:12,143
[SPEAKER_06]: Are you going to protect the triple lock?

574
00:45:12,263 --> 00:45:13,024
[SPEAKER_06]: No, we've said very clearly.

575
00:45:13,044 --> 00:45:14,366
[SPEAKER_06]: Are you going to protect the triple lock?

576
00:45:14,406 --> 00:45:15,767
[SPEAKER_06]: Jeremy, have you not read my manifesto?

577
00:45:15,787 --> 00:45:17,049
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm happy to give you a copy afterwards.

578
00:45:17,069 --> 00:45:18,811
[SPEAKER_06]: I'd love to have one, but I'd like the answer now.

579
00:45:19,051 --> 00:45:20,432
[SPEAKER_14]: Are you going to protect the triple lock?

580
00:45:20,452 --> 00:45:21,994
[SPEAKER_14]: No, they're going to get rid of it, Jeremy.

581
00:45:22,014 --> 00:45:23,416
[SPEAKER_04]: They're going to get rid of it.

582
00:45:23,436 --> 00:45:25,498
[SPEAKER_04]: Amber Rudd, Amber Rudd, can I ask you, please?

583
00:45:25,478 --> 00:45:27,602
[SPEAKER_04]: There are two specific points here.

584
00:45:27,682 --> 00:45:34,774
[SPEAKER_04]: One is about the level of the cap on social care and the other is you also haven't said at what level you'd be means testing the winter fuel payment.

585
00:45:34,814 --> 00:45:41,686
[SPEAKER_06]: We have said we will consult on that but I can tell you very clearly that the billionaires will not be given it.

586
00:45:41,826 --> 00:45:46,474
[SPEAKER_06]: But Jeremy has particularly asked me about looking after pensioners and I would like to answer that.

587
00:45:46,454 --> 00:45:51,163
[SPEAKER_06]: We will always look after pensioners, ensuring they have the dignity and security in retirement.

588
00:45:51,644 --> 00:45:59,058
[SPEAKER_06]: And we have made sure, we have committed to making sure, that their pension will always be uprated according with earnings or inflation.

589
00:45:59,259 --> 00:46:03,687
[SPEAKER_06]: That is so different to the commitment they got under Labour.

590
00:46:03,667 --> 00:46:04,308
[SPEAKER_06]: Tim Farron.

591
00:46:04,329 --> 00:46:05,191
[SPEAKER_16]: I don't have answers to your questions.

592
00:46:05,211 --> 00:46:06,554
[SPEAKER_16]: Amber Ruddy's not answering.

593
00:46:06,574 --> 00:46:06,654
[SPEAKER_16]: Yep.

594
00:46:06,854 --> 00:46:12,568
[SPEAKER_16]: You see, what we have is a general election in eight days' time, Theresa May assuming a colossal landslide.

595
00:46:12,728 --> 00:46:15,595
[SPEAKER_16]: That's why she thinks she can ignore it all and not bother turning up tonight.

596
00:46:15,815 --> 00:46:19,684
[SPEAKER_16]: And she's telling you, we will take you, we will take your house off you.

597
00:46:19,664 --> 00:46:24,491
[SPEAKER_16]: And we will allow you to know how much we'll let you keep after you've given me a colossal majority.

598
00:46:24,711 --> 00:46:31,561
[SPEAKER_16]: So if tonight you resolve to vote Conservative on the 8th of June, you are resolving to give Theresa May permission to do what she likes.

599
00:46:31,581 --> 00:46:33,023
[SPEAKER_16]: And that's with education cuts.

600
00:46:33,043 --> 00:46:37,069
[SPEAKER_16]: That's with NHS cuts.

601
00:46:37,089 --> 00:46:37,690
[SPEAKER_16]: Do not give her a blank check.

602
00:46:38,615 --> 00:46:40,897
[SPEAKER_16]: is how you make things add up.

603
00:46:40,917 --> 00:46:43,580
[SPEAKER_16]: The Liberal Democrats have got a fully costed manifesto.

604
00:46:43,600 --> 00:46:44,281
[SPEAKER_16]: I'll tell you what, though.

605
00:46:44,461 --> 00:46:48,826
[SPEAKER_16]: There's a long-term economic plan underlying the whole of the Liberal Democrat manifesto.

606
00:46:48,866 --> 00:46:56,574
[SPEAKER_16]: And that is, don't leave the European single market and throw away 15 billion pounds every single year in revenue.

607
00:46:56,795 --> 00:47:02,441
[SPEAKER_04]: Just briefly, you have been clear about how you would pay for the extra 6 billion pounds that you would give the NHS.

608
00:47:02,821 --> 00:47:04,603
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you think that would be transformative?

609
00:47:04,623 --> 00:47:08,267
[SPEAKER_04]: Because there are a lot of experts who say that, actually, it wouldn't make that much of a difference.

610
00:47:08,247 --> 00:47:11,371
[SPEAKER_16]: To me, the NHS is personal, not political.

611
00:47:11,752 --> 00:47:26,492
[SPEAKER_16]: My mum, who had ovarian cancer, from the point of her diagnosis, to her treatment, to her care, to her passing away in a ward just two floors away from the one where she'd given birth to me, like everybody out there,

612
00:47:26,472 --> 00:47:29,238
[SPEAKER_16]: our experience with the National Health Service is personal.

613
00:47:29,519 --> 00:47:30,621
[SPEAKER_16]: And let me finish.

614
00:47:30,962 --> 00:47:32,325
[SPEAKER_16]: And the point is simply this.

615
00:47:32,907 --> 00:47:43,350
[SPEAKER_16]: If you look at and you use National Health Services, you know, as we saw in Manchester just last week, how utterly brilliant, caring, dedicated and professional they are.

616
00:47:43,330 --> 00:47:50,598
[SPEAKER_03]: And yet, and yet, Caroline, and yet, and yet, and yet, and yet, Caroline, let me finish, let me finish, let me finish.

617
00:47:50,638 --> 00:47:51,720
[SPEAKER_16]: You know I didn't.

618
00:47:52,260 --> 00:47:58,567
[SPEAKER_16]: So what we've got here is you see the professionalism and the decency of those people, but have we got the best funded health service in the world?

619
00:47:58,868 --> 00:47:59,388
[SPEAKER_16]: No, we haven't.

620
00:47:59,408 --> 00:48:06,196
[SPEAKER_16]: We spend less on our NHS than in Portugal, than on Spain, than on Greece.

621
00:48:06,336 --> 00:48:11,582
[SPEAKER_16]: It's important that we put a penny on income tax to fund the National Health Service and the recovery of it.

622
00:48:12,271 --> 00:48:14,275
[SPEAKER_12]: The question was, how would you raise the money?

623
00:48:14,315 --> 00:48:17,080
[SPEAKER_12]: We've been quite detailed about how we raise the money.

624
00:48:18,282 --> 00:48:24,172
[SPEAKER_12]: Firstly, we'd scrap HS2, which is only there for the benefit of one place and one place alone, and that is London.

625
00:48:24,433 --> 00:48:31,385
[SPEAKER_12]: We'd also look at the Barnard formula, which gives the Scots 1,700 pound per head more than us, the English.

626
00:48:31,585 --> 00:48:32,427
[SPEAKER_12]: It needs to be scrapped.

627
00:48:32,707 --> 00:48:34,070
[SPEAKER_12]: We'd also get an EU dividend.

628
00:48:34,090 --> 00:48:36,574
[SPEAKER_12]: And finally, finally, finally,

629
00:48:36,554 --> 00:48:38,518
[SPEAKER_13]: the famous £350 million a week.

630
00:48:38,538 --> 00:48:45,711
[SPEAKER_12]: We would slash a foreign aid budget which is costing the British people £30 million every single day.

631
00:48:45,791 --> 00:48:54,107
[SPEAKER_12]: And we would transfer that money to the National Health Service and that's why, because we're prepared

632
00:48:54,087 --> 00:48:55,210
[SPEAKER_04]: We can't hear him speak.

633
00:48:55,230 --> 00:49:02,449
[SPEAKER_12]: Because we're prepared to look at different priorities, we can give the NHS an extra £9 billion a year.

634
00:49:02,469 --> 00:49:04,635
[SPEAKER_12]: £2 billion extra for social care.

635
00:49:04,655 --> 00:49:07,963
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not that long ago that you called the NHS a monolithic hangout from days gone by.

636
00:49:07,983 --> 00:49:08,204
[SPEAKER_04]: He did.

637
00:49:08,224 --> 00:49:09,447
[SPEAKER_12]: He said, let's privatise it.

638
00:49:09,427 --> 00:49:11,971
[SPEAKER_04]: When did you change your mind?

639
00:49:11,991 --> 00:49:15,035
[SPEAKER_12]: And in the areas of procurement, I think I was right.

640
00:49:15,115 --> 00:49:16,818
[SPEAKER_12]: I think the NHS could do better.

641
00:49:17,158 --> 00:49:26,431
[SPEAKER_12]: However, what I will say is we're going into this and the last general election with a clear commitment to keep the NHS in public hands and put £9 billion extra in.

642
00:49:26,692 --> 00:49:34,523
[SPEAKER_12]: And that's taking money from a foreign aid budget, as I say, which is costing us at the present moment £13 billion every single year.

643
00:49:34,503 --> 00:49:37,746
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you all for your responses to that question.

644
00:49:37,806 --> 00:49:46,234
[SPEAKER_04]: Just a reminder that if you want to have your say on tonight's debate, you can join the conversation on social media using the hashtag BBC debate.

645
00:49:46,534 --> 00:49:55,142
[SPEAKER_04]: We still have time for more questions from our audience here in Cambridge, and we can go to the next of those questions now, and it comes from David Mansfield.

646
00:49:55,563 --> 00:49:56,083
[SPEAKER_00]: Good evening.

647
00:49:56,864 --> 00:50:01,388
[SPEAKER_00]: What are your priorities for making Britain a safer country and the world a safer place?

648
00:50:02,127 --> 00:50:02,568
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

649
00:50:02,848 --> 00:50:08,217
[SPEAKER_04]: How would you make, what are your priorities for making Britain a safer country and the world a safer place?

650
00:50:08,718 --> 00:50:09,419
[SPEAKER_04]: Angus Robinson.

651
00:50:09,840 --> 00:50:22,902
[SPEAKER_13]: Well the first thing is I imagine at the forefront of your minds, and I'm sure I speak for all of my colleagues here, at the forefront of all of our minds are all of the families who suffered the devastation to their loved ones and relatives with the attack on Manchester.

652
00:50:22,942 --> 00:50:28,371
[SPEAKER_13]: What happened there was a horror and sadly it's happening

653
00:50:28,351 --> 00:50:31,375
[SPEAKER_13]: far too often, both here and round about the world.

654
00:50:31,415 --> 00:50:37,424
[SPEAKER_13]: So I think the first thing that we need to do is that we do need to take safety and security seriously.

655
00:50:38,085 --> 00:50:42,071
[SPEAKER_13]: We need to invest in the police, not cut them as has been the case in England.

656
00:50:42,591 --> 00:50:44,694
[SPEAKER_13]: In Scotland, we've managed to maintain police numbers.

657
00:50:44,835 --> 00:50:45,856
[SPEAKER_13]: So that's my first step.

658
00:50:45,876 --> 00:50:51,985
[SPEAKER_13]: Let's make sure we back the police, give the resources that they need, back our intelligence services who do a tremendous job.

659
00:50:52,365 --> 00:50:57,733
[SPEAKER_13]: There's been some discussion, has there not, about the link between UK foreign policy and

660
00:50:57,713 --> 00:50:59,855
[SPEAKER_13]: becoming perhaps a terrorist threat.

661
00:50:59,935 --> 00:51:01,897
[SPEAKER_13]: And I think that's a dangerous link to draw.

662
00:51:02,177 --> 00:51:03,258
[SPEAKER_13]: However, I would say this.

663
00:51:03,978 --> 00:51:08,262
[SPEAKER_13]: I think we are right to question our intervention in different parts of the world.

664
00:51:08,742 --> 00:51:11,425
[SPEAKER_13]: In Afghanistan, in Iraq, in Libya.

665
00:51:11,825 --> 00:51:16,369
[SPEAKER_13]: And the lesson I draw from that is not that it is wrong sometimes to intervene.

666
00:51:16,789 --> 00:51:19,111
[SPEAKER_13]: We agreed that helping people in Libya was a good thing.

667
00:51:19,532 --> 00:51:26,758
[SPEAKER_13]: But what was wrong was spending 13 times more bombing that country than helping to rebuild it.

668
00:51:26,738 --> 00:51:28,834
[SPEAKER_13]: on leaving areas of the world.

669
00:51:31,042 --> 00:51:38,468
[SPEAKER_13]: Leaving areas of the world with ungoverned spaces is where terrorism and extremism thrives.

670
00:51:38,488 --> 00:51:45,835
[SPEAKER_13]: So we need to do everything that we can to counter extremist thought, give the police and security service the tools that they require.

671
00:51:46,155 --> 00:51:51,139
[SPEAKER_13]: So not cutting the police would be a first step that I would take from Scotland's experience.

672
00:51:51,159 --> 00:51:54,502
[SPEAKER_13]: And I think we want to be very cautious about how we intervene internationally.

673
00:51:54,762 --> 00:52:00,087
[SPEAKER_13]: And if we're going to do it, we have to think long and hard about how we make sure that those places remain stable

674
00:52:00,067 --> 00:52:01,489
[SPEAKER_13]: and safe for years to come.

675
00:52:01,529 --> 00:52:07,699
[SPEAKER_04]: Jeremy Corbyn, you have talked about our foreign interventions and our safety here at home.

676
00:52:08,440 --> 00:52:12,226
[SPEAKER_14]: What happened in Manchester was unbelievably abominable in every way.

677
00:52:12,667 --> 00:52:16,353
[SPEAKER_14]: Innocent lives were taken of mainly young women out enjoying themselves.

678
00:52:16,453 --> 00:52:22,362
[SPEAKER_14]: I want to live in a country that protects the right of people to go out and enjoy themselves at any town or any city in this country.

679
00:52:22,865 --> 00:52:32,495
[SPEAKER_14]: The consequences of that are appalling for those families, and I hope those that are perpetrated this act are all discovered and brought to book.

680
00:52:33,176 --> 00:52:36,660
[SPEAKER_14]: But there's also a question we have to ask about the number of police officers.

681
00:52:37,281 --> 00:52:44,188
[SPEAKER_14]: Under Amber Rudd's time in the Home Secretary and Theresa May before that, 20,000 police officers have lost their jobs.

682
00:52:44,609 --> 00:52:50,475
[SPEAKER_14]: There are fewer police officers around than there were seven years ago, and those cuts are going to continue.

683
00:52:50,455 --> 00:52:53,140
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it's important that we restore that.

684
00:52:53,160 --> 00:53:00,575
[SPEAKER_14]: What I also think, if I may say so, is the point that Angus was alluding to about terror threats and other threats to our security.

685
00:53:00,916 --> 00:53:03,180
[SPEAKER_14]: There are terrorist threats, obviously.

686
00:53:03,380 --> 00:53:07,789
[SPEAKER_14]: There are also cyber attacks threats, as the National Health Service discovered.

687
00:53:07,769 --> 00:53:22,212
[SPEAKER_14]: It's also important that we recognize that leaving large spaces of, for example, Libya, ungoverned, leaves an opportunity for those who wish to do harm to an awful lot of people, a space in which to develop to do that harm.

688
00:53:22,773 --> 00:53:26,840
[SPEAKER_14]: If you intervene somewhere, the consequences go on for a very long time.

689
00:53:26,880 --> 00:53:34,232
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you think on the police cuts, without the police cuts, are you saying the attack in Manchester wouldn't have happened?

690
00:53:34,212 --> 00:53:35,896
[SPEAKER_14]: No, I'm absolutely not saying that.

691
00:53:35,916 --> 00:53:48,805
[SPEAKER_14]: The attack in Manchester happened because somebody decided that they wanted to go and kill a large number of people for some perverted belief in their minds.

692
00:53:49,226 --> 00:53:50,449
[SPEAKER_14]: They have to be

693
00:53:51,509 --> 00:53:55,093
[SPEAKER_14]: dealt with and those people that were under threat have to be protected.

694
00:53:55,334 --> 00:54:10,071
[SPEAKER_14]: What I'm also saying is though, it would be extremely unwise for any government to ignore, any government anywhere in the world, to ignore what is happening in Libya where large areas are left ungoverned and very dangerous forces are arising there.

695
00:54:10,292 --> 00:54:21,465
[SPEAKER_14]: What we need to do is recognise the human rights and justice of people all around the world and be prepared to support them, not just go in and bomb and do nothing about it afterwards.

696
00:54:21,445 --> 00:54:27,232
[SPEAKER_04]: is what happened in London.

697
00:54:27,252 --> 00:54:30,536
[SPEAKER_04]: Just a quick point of fact before I turn to Amber Rudd.

698
00:54:30,837 --> 00:54:33,159
[SPEAKER_04]: Diane Abbott has talked about 10,000 more police officers.

699
00:54:33,179 --> 00:54:33,900
[SPEAKER_04]: You're saying 20,000.

700
00:54:33,920 --> 00:54:37,505
[SPEAKER_14]: No, I said 20,000 have been cut by the Conservative government.

701
00:54:37,525 --> 00:54:39,347
[SPEAKER_14]: We would put 10,000 more on.

702
00:54:39,527 --> 00:54:41,850
[SPEAKER_14]: What I would also want to add, and I think it's important,

703
00:54:41,830 --> 00:54:45,397
[SPEAKER_14]: is the response of people in this country to what happened in Manchester.

704
00:54:45,417 --> 00:54:51,570
[SPEAKER_14]: I was in Manchester straight after the event took place, and Tim was there as well, and Amber.

705
00:54:51,590 --> 00:54:54,997
[SPEAKER_14]: The most amazing sense of community unity came together.

706
00:54:55,217 --> 00:55:00,488
[SPEAKER_14]: They were not going to allow that individual who killed those people to divide our communities.

707
00:55:00,508 --> 00:55:02,893
[SPEAKER_14]: They were going to be united and responsible.

708
00:55:05,607 --> 00:55:07,150
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

709
00:55:07,170 --> 00:55:13,742
[SPEAKER_06]: It's a really important question, because the first job of any government is to keep its citizens safe and secure.

710
00:55:14,363 --> 00:55:15,726
[SPEAKER_06]: But I'm going to level with you.

711
00:55:15,846 --> 00:55:23,059
[SPEAKER_06]: Since 2014, we have been at the threat level of severe, which means an attack is highly likely.

712
00:55:23,039 --> 00:55:34,878
