898
01:07:55,529 --> 01:08:01,057
[SPEAKER_16]: You see the mass movement of people as our land is desiccated and deluged by that climate change.

899
01:08:01,077 --> 01:08:02,559
[SPEAKER_16]: So the reality is simply this.

900
01:08:03,060 --> 01:08:10,270
[SPEAKER_16]: If it is simply for hair-shirt, muesli-eating Guardian readers to solve climate change, it ain't going to solve the problem.

901
01:08:10,310 --> 01:08:11,051
[SPEAKER_16]: We're all stuffed.

902
01:08:11,292 --> 01:08:13,855
[SPEAKER_16]: So let's do something that will actually make a difference.

903
01:08:14,096 --> 01:08:19,864
[SPEAKER_16]: And that means a nationwide, indeed a planet-wide, concerted effort to build the future that we need.

904
01:08:19,904 --> 01:08:20,625
[SPEAKER_16]: So for Britain,

905
01:08:20,605 --> 01:08:21,266
[SPEAKER_16]: What can we do?

906
01:08:21,587 --> 01:08:25,393
[SPEAKER_16]: We can make ourselves energy self-sufficient in renewable energy.

907
01:08:25,413 --> 01:08:34,469
[SPEAKER_16]: 95% of the supply chain of energy in this country, of wind, of tidal and marine and coastal energy is British made.

908
01:08:34,690 --> 01:08:38,376
[SPEAKER_16]: Why not rebuild our economy whilst guaranteeing our children's future?

909
01:08:38,416 --> 01:08:39,778
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

910
01:08:39,799 --> 01:08:40,099
[SPEAKER_05]: Caroline Lucas.

911
01:08:41,868 --> 01:08:50,500
[SPEAKER_05]: I just want to thank that so much for that question, because the Green Party has been trying to get climate change onto this election campaign agenda for the past six weeks.

912
01:08:50,580 --> 01:08:51,381
[SPEAKER_05]: It has been impossible.

913
01:08:51,421 --> 01:08:53,103
[SPEAKER_05]: So thank you so much for that.

914
01:08:53,544 --> 01:08:54,805
[SPEAKER_05]: It is a vital question.

915
01:08:54,845 --> 01:08:56,327
[SPEAKER_05]: It is the greatest threat that we face.

916
01:08:56,347 --> 01:09:01,574
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think, first of all, in terms of what we do to President Trump, I'm trying to think of a polite answer.

917
01:09:01,615 --> 01:09:10,947
[SPEAKER_05]: But I think essentially what we need to do actually is ignore him, because the economics behind renewables

918
01:09:11,399 --> 01:09:19,353
[SPEAKER_05]: It's already such that we know that renewables are going to be cheaper than the fossil fuels that they already replace.

919
01:09:19,373 --> 01:09:21,177
[SPEAKER_05]: So that revolution is already happening.

920
01:09:21,197 --> 01:09:26,346
[SPEAKER_05]: But what we need to do in this country is an awful lot more than is being done by this government or, indeed, previous ones.

921
01:09:26,706 --> 01:09:30,353
[SPEAKER_05]: First of all, we need to leave 2 thirds of all known fossil fuel

922
01:09:30,333 --> 01:09:35,061
[SPEAKER_05]: fossil fuels in the ground if we're to have any hope of avoiding catastrophic climate change.

923
01:09:35,101 --> 01:09:38,526
[SPEAKER_05]: That means a massive investment in renewable energy, energy efficiency.

924
01:09:39,047 --> 01:09:47,801
[SPEAKER_05]: Amber Rudd, of course, was the Energy Secretary for a while, but under her we did not see the kind of transition we urgently need to see if we're serious about climate change.

925
01:09:47,821 --> 01:09:51,648
[SPEAKER_05]: So we do need to see keeping fossil fuels in the ground, not giving fossil fuel subsidies.

926
01:09:51,968 --> 01:09:54,332
[SPEAKER_05]: We need to see no fracking, not the kind of frack

927
01:09:54,312 --> 01:09:58,627
[SPEAKER_05]: tracking that is being planned all around the country under this government.

928
01:09:58,647 --> 01:10:01,718
[SPEAKER_04]: We also need to see an end to massive airport expansion.

929
01:10:01,738 --> 01:10:04,246
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm going to stop you, Caroline Lucas, because we're going to...

930
01:10:04,267 --> 01:10:05,150
[SPEAKER_04]: There is lots more to say.

931
01:10:05,270 --> 01:10:06,735
[SPEAKER_04]: I want to turn to Paul Nuttall.

932
01:10:07,070 --> 01:10:10,455
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, President Trump is doing what he set out to do.

933
01:10:10,535 --> 01:10:13,719
[SPEAKER_12]: I mean, he is the leader of the free world, whether we like it or not.

934
01:10:13,779 --> 01:10:18,145
[SPEAKER_12]: He said during his election campaign that he would withdraw from the Paris Agreement.

935
01:10:18,205 --> 01:10:29,300
[SPEAKER_12]: What he's doing is he's looking at India and he's looking at China, who've got huge coal-fired power station building programs, which are taking place at this present moment in time.

936
01:10:29,340 --> 01:10:30,462
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you think he's doing the right thing, then?

937
01:10:30,442 --> 01:10:34,731
[SPEAKER_12]: He's looking at the US economy, and he promised to look after the Rust Belt and working class people.

938
01:10:35,052 --> 01:10:42,609
[SPEAKER_12]: And he knows that if they reduce energy bills, and they will do that by withdrawing from the Paris Agreement, then he will protect the American economy.

939
01:10:42,629 --> 01:10:43,851
[SPEAKER_12]: He's putting America first.

940
01:10:43,871 --> 01:10:47,860
[SPEAKER_12]: And frankly, I think Britain should put Britain first as well.

941
01:10:48,886 --> 01:10:51,790
[SPEAKER_04]: So you would want to see Britain doing the same, then?

942
01:10:51,810 --> 01:10:54,713
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, you know, we are only to blame for 2% of global emissions.

943
01:10:54,733 --> 01:11:01,542
[SPEAKER_12]: And what's going to happen is if energy prices continue to go up, companies will move to countries with lower environmental standards.

944
01:11:01,562 --> 01:11:02,283
[SPEAKER_04]: Jeremy Corbyn.

945
01:11:02,303 --> 01:11:05,246
[SPEAKER_14]: We should absolutely adhere to the Paris climate change agreement.

946
01:11:05,547 --> 01:11:12,295
[SPEAKER_14]: And we should urge the American people to press their government, their Senate, and their House, and their president to adhere to it as well.

947
01:11:14,502 --> 01:11:21,371
[SPEAKER_14]: In this country, we are determined to achieve 60% of renewable energy by 2030.

948
01:11:22,152 --> 01:11:24,174
[SPEAKER_14]: We're also determined to reduce emissions.

949
01:11:24,455 --> 01:11:27,258
[SPEAKER_14]: But it's not just about climate change emissions.

950
01:11:27,498 --> 01:11:35,669
[SPEAKER_14]: It's also about our attitude towards the environment, levels of air quality, and air pollution in our cities, which are not being addressed by this government.

951
01:11:35,689 --> 01:11:41,556
[SPEAKER_14]: And also, when we did have a growing and thriving solar power industry in this country, what did they do?

952
01:11:41,536 --> 01:11:45,626
[SPEAKER_14]: cut the feed-in tariffs, which destroyed and damaged a lot of that industry.

953
01:11:45,646 --> 01:11:46,889
[SPEAKER_04]: We need a different approach.

954
01:11:47,050 --> 01:11:55,812
[SPEAKER_04]: Amber Rudd, the UK's own official advisers say that your government's not on track to meet the pledge of cutting emissions 80% by 2050.

955
01:11:56,253 --> 01:11:56,794
[SPEAKER_04]: Why not?

956
01:11:57,044 --> 01:11:59,928
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm going to answer the first question, if I may, about the Paris climate change agreement.

957
01:11:59,948 --> 01:12:02,232
[SPEAKER_06]: And I must tell you, I am disappointed.

958
01:12:02,592 --> 01:12:03,434
[SPEAKER_06]: Caroline is right.

959
01:12:03,654 --> 01:12:10,404
[SPEAKER_06]: I led the UK delegation to get that international agreement of 180 different countries pledging to that reduction.

960
01:12:10,825 --> 01:12:12,848
[SPEAKER_06]: And it is disappointing that the Americans are pulling out.

961
01:12:12,868 --> 01:12:22,302
[SPEAKER_06]: But I hope that we can use our relationship with President Trump and our close relationship with the US to try and influence, to try and make sure they nevertheless take the right step.

962
01:12:22,322 --> 01:12:22,863
[SPEAKER_11]: Tell him he's wrong.

963
01:12:22,883 --> 01:12:23,664
[SPEAKER_11]: Tell him he is wrong.

964
01:12:23,684 --> 01:12:25,667
[SPEAKER_06]: That's not quite how diplomacy works.

965
01:12:25,647 --> 01:12:35,418
[SPEAKER_06]: The reason why I am optimistic is because there has been such substantial investment in renewable energy.

966
01:12:35,478 --> 01:12:40,003
[SPEAKER_06]: And yes, in solar, it is increasingly doesn't need a subsidy.

967
01:12:40,023 --> 01:12:45,269
[SPEAKER_06]: So because of that investment, it makes good economic sense as well as good renewable energy.

968
01:12:45,289 --> 01:12:46,391
[SPEAKER_14]: What about air pollution?

969
01:12:46,451 --> 01:12:48,653
[SPEAKER_14]: Can we take the court over air pollution?

970
01:12:48,793 --> 01:12:53,959
[SPEAKER_11]: This is terrible leadership on the part of Donald Trump.

971
01:12:54,080 --> 01:12:55,401
[SPEAKER_11]: It's also appalling leadership.

972
01:12:55,381 --> 01:13:01,471
[SPEAKER_11]: on behalf of the Prime Minister, who can't even be bothered to come here and answer these questions for herself today.

973
01:13:04,436 --> 01:13:05,838
[SPEAKER_11]: But it's no surprise either.

974
01:13:05,919 --> 01:13:12,990
[SPEAKER_11]: He was very clear during his election campaign what it was he would be about in terms of climate change, and he is sticking to his line.

975
01:13:13,090 --> 01:13:16,897
[SPEAKER_11]: But he is wrong, and the world needs to tell him he is wrong.

976
01:13:17,137 --> 01:13:18,039
[SPEAKER_11]: It's bad business.

977
01:13:18,059 --> 01:13:18,960
[SPEAKER_11]: It's bad, bad business.

978
01:13:18,980 --> 01:13:20,022
[SPEAKER_11]: Angus Robertson.

979
01:13:20,052 --> 01:13:23,096
[SPEAKER_13]: So to answer the question, I'm more than disappointed.

980
01:13:23,116 --> 01:13:31,127
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm appalled that President Trump has walked away from a global approach to one of the biggest challenges that we face at home and abroad.

981
01:13:31,528 --> 01:13:35,093
[SPEAKER_13]: And what he's done is what many of us fear he's going to do in a number of different ways.

982
01:13:35,153 --> 01:13:42,263
[SPEAKER_13]: He's walking away from having a multilateral approach, working together with other countries to deal with serious problems.

983
01:13:42,243 --> 01:14:02,226
[SPEAKER_13]: And that's why if the UK had a special relationship with the United States, and we remember of course the first trip that was made by Theresa May was to see a climate change denier, namely Donald Trump, what kind of influence was used by the Prime Minister then to make sure that he didn't go forward with this disastrous step?

984
01:14:02,206 --> 01:14:04,049
[SPEAKER_13]: Absolutely nothing.

985
01:14:04,089 --> 01:14:08,757
[SPEAKER_13]: This is a government that has got rid of the climate change responsibility at the cabinet table.

986
01:14:09,078 --> 01:14:10,861
[SPEAKER_13]: It is absolutely appalling.

987
01:14:10,881 --> 01:14:13,966
[SPEAKER_13]: So what we need to do is we need to do everything that we can at home.

988
01:14:14,347 --> 01:14:19,075
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm delighted that more than 50% of all electricity generated in Scotland is now through renewables.

989
01:14:19,436 --> 01:14:24,945
[SPEAKER_13]: We would have loved to have gone ahead with carbon capture and storage until Amber and her colleagues scrapped it.

990
01:14:25,005 --> 01:14:26,728
[SPEAKER_13]: So there's much more that can be done.

991
01:14:26,708 --> 01:14:38,362
[SPEAKER_13]: So the Prime Minister and her government need to take climate change seriously in a way that they haven't done in recent years, and we need to impress on all of our international colleagues that we need to work together and get this global challenge sorted.

992
01:14:38,782 --> 01:14:41,606
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you for all the responses to that particular question.

993
01:14:41,666 --> 01:14:47,533
[SPEAKER_04]: And it's time now for our last question of the evening, and it comes from Neil Plucknett.

994
01:14:49,795 --> 01:14:56,243
[SPEAKER_09]: In what way does your leadership have the talent and the character required to take this country forward into the future?

995
01:14:56,780 --> 01:14:57,240
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

996
01:14:57,481 --> 01:15:04,328
[SPEAKER_04]: In what way does your leadership have the talent and the character needed to take this country forward?

997
01:15:04,508 --> 01:15:06,791
[SPEAKER_04]: Jeremy Corbyn.

998
01:15:06,811 --> 01:15:17,842
[SPEAKER_14]: Leadership is about understanding the people you represent, is about being prepared to learn, is about not being so high and mighty you can't take advice.

999
01:15:18,483 --> 01:15:20,825
[SPEAKER_14]: It is also about bringing people with you.

1000
01:15:21,166 --> 01:15:24,289
[SPEAKER_14]: It is also about ensuring that your responsibilities

1001
01:15:24,269 --> 01:15:39,985
[SPEAKER_14]: protect the safety and security of everybody in this country and to lead a government that cares for everybody in the country and doesn't walk by on the other side when there are people that are homeless, there are people that are starving and we have millions of our children living in poverty.

1002
01:15:40,386 --> 01:15:48,454
[SPEAKER_14]: It's leadership to lead a government that is prepared to say to our society we cannot go on like this, we have to start

1003
01:15:48,434 --> 01:15:51,619
[SPEAKER_14]: putting more money into our public services and our resources.

1004
01:15:51,879 --> 01:16:13,311
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to have an economy that works for all and we don't have to have a spiv economy that hands tax relief to the biggest corporations and the wealthiest people whilst ignoring the desperate cries for social help of so many people in our country.

1005
01:16:16,953 --> 01:16:18,876
[SPEAKER_04]: Paul Nuttall, your leadership?

1006
01:16:18,896 --> 01:16:22,161
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, I've never changed my stance, pretty much, on anything.

1007
01:16:22,562 --> 01:16:23,864
[SPEAKER_12]: I don't flip-flop.

1008
01:16:23,884 --> 01:16:26,708
[SPEAKER_12]: I've always been, for example, a Brexiteer.

1009
01:16:26,948 --> 01:16:30,814
[SPEAKER_12]: And look, you know, back when I joined UKIP, you don't join UKIP for a career.

1010
01:16:30,874 --> 01:16:33,058
[SPEAKER_12]: You join it because you've got principles.

1011
01:16:33,098 --> 01:16:34,560
[SPEAKER_12]: And our principle was simply this.

1012
01:16:34,961 --> 01:16:37,665
[SPEAKER_12]: We wanted to get our country out of the European Union.

1013
01:16:37,945 --> 01:16:41,070
[SPEAKER_12]: And we were very successful on June the 23rd.

1014
01:16:41,050 --> 01:16:41,671
[SPEAKER_12]: last year.

1015
01:16:41,951 --> 01:16:48,823
[SPEAKER_12]: Now, what we've got to do is we've got to ensure that we get the Brexit that people voted for.

1016
01:16:48,963 --> 01:16:52,489
[SPEAKER_12]: A Brexit whereby we control our own borders and cut immigration.

1017
01:16:52,529 --> 01:16:55,694
[SPEAKER_12]: We get full control of our waters back and our fisheries.

1018
01:16:55,994 --> 01:16:59,881
[SPEAKER_12]: We take full control of our laws and bring them back to Westminster.

1019
01:16:59,901 --> 01:17:00,662
[SPEAKER_12]: We leave

1020
01:17:00,642 --> 01:17:04,407
[SPEAKER_12]: the ECJ and indeed the ECHR.

1021
01:17:04,427 --> 01:17:09,533
[SPEAKER_12]: We're free to sign our own trade deals all over the globe and we're out of the single market.

1022
01:17:09,713 --> 01:17:15,040
[SPEAKER_12]: And, most importantly, we pay no divorce bill to the European Union.

1023
01:17:15,080 --> 01:17:22,989
[SPEAKER_12]: Because since we've been members, since 1973, we've paid £183 billion net in membership fee alone.

1024
01:17:23,510 --> 01:17:25,532
[SPEAKER_12]: I'd be strong enough going into these negotiations.

1025
01:17:25,813 --> 01:17:27,295
[SPEAKER_12]: I just hope the Prime Minister is as strong.

1026
01:17:27,315 --> 01:17:30,058
[SPEAKER_10]: Would you refuse to pay your dues if we were going through a real divorce then?

1027
01:17:30,038 --> 01:17:32,913
[SPEAKER_10]: Would you refuse to pay your dues if you were going through a real divorce?

1028
01:17:33,114 --> 01:17:36,572
[SPEAKER_10]: Well, look, listen, we have given...

1029
01:17:38,847 --> 01:17:40,189
[SPEAKER_12]: Good question.

1030
01:17:40,209 --> 01:17:43,352
[SPEAKER_12]: We have given that club £183 billion since 1973.

1031
01:17:43,753 --> 01:17:48,898
[SPEAKER_12]: We've got £9 billion tied up in the European Investment Bank and indeed we own lots of it.

1032
01:17:49,019 --> 01:17:51,141
[SPEAKER_12]: We all know about blokes like you.

1033
01:17:51,181 --> 01:17:52,482
[SPEAKER_11]: We all know about blokes like you.

1034
01:17:52,503 --> 01:17:53,784
[SPEAKER_12]: Listen, don't talk down this country.

1035
01:17:53,804 --> 01:17:55,686
[SPEAKER_12]: We are the fifth largest economy in the world.

1036
01:17:55,706 --> 01:17:56,347
[SPEAKER_11]: You want a free divorce?

1037
01:17:56,367 --> 01:17:57,228
[SPEAKER_11]: It doesn't happen that way.

1038
01:17:57,248 --> 01:17:59,430
[SPEAKER_11]: In the real world there's no such thing as a free divorce.

1039
01:17:59,450 --> 01:18:00,872
[SPEAKER_11]: You have to pay your dues.

1040
01:18:00,852 --> 01:18:06,419
[SPEAKER_12]: But this, look, look, look, this is all about, listen, listen, this is all about trade.

1041
01:18:06,599 --> 01:18:08,561
[SPEAKER_12]: And we have a huge trade deficit with the EU.

1042
01:18:08,621 --> 01:18:10,604
[SPEAKER_12]: They need us more than we need them.

1043
01:18:10,684 --> 01:18:13,367
[SPEAKER_12]: For God's sake, let's be confident about ourselves.

1044
01:18:13,527 --> 01:18:23,038
[SPEAKER_04]: Amber Rudd, the question is about leadership and the Conservatives have made a lot of noise about Theresa May's leadership, personal leadership.

1045
01:18:23,199 --> 01:18:26,843
[SPEAKER_04]: And yet this is a campaign where we saw a major U-turn on social care.

1046
01:18:26,823 --> 01:18:37,119
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, part of being a good leader is having a good strong team around you and I'm proud and delighted to be here representing the Conservative Party and the Prime Minister making that case.

1047
01:18:37,499 --> 01:18:40,764
[SPEAKER_06]: Let's face it, Jeremy only decided to come I think late this morning.

1048
01:18:40,784 --> 01:18:45,051
[SPEAKER_06]: I was rather hoping Diane Abbott might be here so I could debate with her as well.

1049
01:18:45,031 --> 01:18:54,264
[SPEAKER_06]: But the fact is the most important challenge that this government is going to have going forward is getting a good negotiation with the EU.

1050
01:18:54,604 --> 01:19:01,194
[SPEAKER_06]: It's going to dictate whether we have a strong economy, whether we can pay good wages to our public servants and support our public services.

1051
01:19:01,634 --> 01:19:04,378
[SPEAKER_06]: Theresa May has the support of her team.

1052
01:19:04,659 --> 01:19:07,242
[SPEAKER_06]: She has the support of whoever becomes her MPs.

1053
01:19:07,643 --> 01:19:14,953
[SPEAKER_06]: Jeremy Corbyn has had a no-confidence vote against him, which four out of five of his MPs wouldn't support him on.

1054
01:19:14,933 --> 01:19:21,823
[SPEAKER_06]: How can he go in to negotiate with 27 different countries with such a weak team and weak support behind him?

1055
01:19:22,083 --> 01:19:24,948
[SPEAKER_06]: Theresa May will be able to deliver for us.

1056
01:19:25,328 --> 01:19:28,833
[SPEAKER_06]: As Home Secretary, she delivered 35 different opt-outs.

1057
01:19:29,094 --> 01:19:32,459
[SPEAKER_06]: She knows how to negotiate and deliver for the European Union.

1058
01:19:32,819 --> 01:19:33,881
[SPEAKER_06]: She'll be the right leader for us.

1059
01:19:34,221 --> 01:19:37,426
[SPEAKER_04]: OK. Jeremy Corbyn, can you respond to that point about the result of your MPs?

1060
01:19:37,446 --> 01:19:41,532
[SPEAKER_14]: 300,000 people elected me to lead this party, and I'm very proud to lead this party.

1061
01:19:47,418 --> 01:19:48,181
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't know why I'm moving.

1062
01:19:49,645 --> 01:19:52,668
[SPEAKER_05]: I think the first rule of leadership is to show up.

1063
01:19:53,129 --> 01:19:58,915
[SPEAKER_05]: You don't call a general election.

1064
01:19:58,935 --> 01:20:05,181
[SPEAKER_05]: You don't call a general election and say it's the most important election in her lifetime, and then not even be bothered to come and debate the issues at stake.

1065
01:20:05,641 --> 01:20:12,509
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, I feel quite unique here tonight as a co-leader, and I'm proud that the Green Party pioneers new ways of doing things.

1066
01:20:12,909 --> 01:20:18,775
[SPEAKER_05]: We want to see job sharing in all kinds of aspects of our lives, because we believe that two heads are often better than one,

1067
01:20:18,755 --> 01:20:21,820
[SPEAKER_05]: And so I'm very happy to be there with my co-leader, Jonathan Bartley.

1068
01:20:22,361 --> 01:20:25,266
[SPEAKER_05]: But what leadership is about, it is about listening.

1069
01:20:25,286 --> 01:20:28,351
[SPEAKER_05]: It is about recognizing that all of us have leadership qualities.

1070
01:20:28,732 --> 01:20:31,596
[SPEAKER_05]: And in particular, I think it's about trusting the public.

1071
01:20:31,616 --> 01:20:36,865
[SPEAKER_05]: And on that issue, I do not understand why this government will not allow the people

1072
01:20:36,845 --> 01:20:39,148
[SPEAKER_05]: to have the final say on the EU referendum.

1073
01:20:39,468 --> 01:20:46,317
[SPEAKER_05]: Why can we not have a ratification referendum when we see the final deal of what Theresa May or whoever it is brings back from Brussels?

1074
01:20:46,757 --> 01:20:50,021
[SPEAKER_05]: Why can we not trust the British people to have that final say?

1075
01:20:50,081 --> 01:20:52,064
[SPEAKER_05]: If they like what they see, that's great.

1076
01:20:52,384 --> 01:21:03,237
[SPEAKER_05]: But if they don't, the way to have another look at that is by voting Green, because we will say on that ballot paper that you should have the right to remain in the EU if that's what you choose when you see the small print.

1077
01:21:03,618 --> 01:21:05,400
[SPEAKER_05]: Because since this referendum was called,

1078
01:21:05,380 --> 01:21:07,643
[SPEAKER_05]: We have so many lies told.

1079
01:21:07,663 --> 01:21:11,668
[SPEAKER_04]: What are your qualities of leadership?

1080
01:21:12,028 --> 01:21:14,171
[SPEAKER_16]: Good leaders don't run away from a debate.

1081
01:21:14,491 --> 01:21:16,414
[SPEAKER_16]: Theresa May undoubtedly should be here.

1082
01:21:16,994 --> 01:21:23,142
[SPEAKER_16]: Whatever we have discussed this evening, her absence is undoubtedly the shadow that hangs over this election.

1083
01:21:23,162 --> 01:21:29,430
[SPEAKER_16]: How dare you call a general election and then run away from the debate?

1084
01:21:31,823 --> 01:21:38,128
[SPEAKER_16]: We are all products of our upbringing.

1085
01:21:38,188 --> 01:21:40,170
[SPEAKER_16]: So I was brought up in Preston during the 1980s.

1086
01:21:40,951 --> 01:21:50,199
[SPEAKER_16]: And I saw people around me, what happens when a society, a community, is taken for granted, in that case, by a conservative government with a colossal majority.

1087
01:21:50,259 --> 01:21:53,922
[SPEAKER_16]: Half my mates' parents out at work at any given time.

1088
01:21:54,182 --> 01:22:01,088
[SPEAKER_16]: And I am determined to build a country for our kids, mine included, where people are decent to one another, where people have enough.

1089
01:22:01,068 --> 01:22:03,710
[SPEAKER_16]: We have a national health service that is properly funded.

1090
01:22:03,911 --> 01:22:08,655
[SPEAKER_16]: And that means being honest with the British people, saying we will put a penny on income tax to have the best health service in the world.

1091
01:22:08,935 --> 01:22:14,600
[SPEAKER_16]: It means stopping Theresa May's plans to do to your kids' schools what she's currently doing to our hospitals.

1092
01:22:14,640 --> 01:22:21,126
[SPEAKER_16]: And it also means if you want to lead the people, you have to kind of like them as well and spend time amongst them.

1093
01:22:21,346 --> 01:22:28,393
[SPEAKER_16]: And if you trust the people, then you do not impose that Brexit deal on the British people without them having the final say.

1094
01:22:28,653 --> 01:22:31,075
[SPEAKER_16]: Either the politicians will sign it off or the people will.

1095
01:22:31,055 --> 01:22:32,959
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, I trust the people.

1096
01:22:38,129 --> 01:22:53,299
[SPEAKER_13]: So real leadership is about putting the country before you put your party and I think we all now know that this was a totally unnecessary election and the only reason Theresa May called it was that she thought she was going to have a massive majority as a result of it.

1097
01:22:53,279 --> 01:22:55,104
[SPEAKER_13]: whatever happened to strength and stability?

1098
01:22:55,966 --> 01:22:57,992
[SPEAKER_13]: Where's strength and stability gone?

1099
01:22:58,152 --> 01:23:02,885
[SPEAKER_13]: Weak and wobbly is where we are, not so much the Iron Lady as the U-turn Queen.

1100
01:23:03,046 --> 01:23:05,332
[SPEAKER_13]: That is not the leadership that we require.

1101
01:23:06,114 --> 01:23:07,137
[SPEAKER_13]: In contrast,

1102
01:23:08,483 --> 01:23:25,911
[SPEAKER_13]: In contrast, as leader of the SNP in the House of Commons, the third party in the House of Commons, I am proud that we have led the effective opposition when sadly the Labour Party has too often dropped the ball, asking questions not just about things that matter to people in Scotland but the rest of the UK, in Europe and the world.

1103
01:23:26,011 --> 01:23:33,563
[SPEAKER_13]: And I am confident that the SNP will be returned to Westminster as the third party because we need to protect our country from the Tories who sadly

1104
01:23:33,543 --> 01:23:35,727
[SPEAKER_13]: I fear are going to win this election.

1105
01:23:35,908 --> 01:23:55,247
[SPEAKER_13]: I am working hard to win in every single seat in Scotland, Misha, that is our plan, but I believe people in Scotland realise that it's either the SNP or it's the Tories, and whether they're Labour voters, Liberal Democrats or Greens, they understand that if they vote for those parties they'll be doing nothing but helping the Tories.

1106
01:23:55,227 --> 01:24:04,135
[SPEAKER_11]: I believe leaders should walk the walk and should be prepared to defend their politics and their policies.

1107
01:24:04,595 --> 01:24:06,957
[SPEAKER_11]: They should also be prepared to stick to their guns.

1108
01:24:07,117 --> 01:24:10,520
[SPEAKER_11]: And it's shocking that Theresa May has u-turned on so many things.

1109
01:24:10,560 --> 01:24:11,962
[SPEAKER_11]: There wasn't going to be an election.

1110
01:24:12,002 --> 01:24:13,623
[SPEAKER_11]: Now there's an election.

1111
01:24:13,703 --> 01:24:21,590
[SPEAKER_11]: There wasn't going to be a tax on the self-employed, or there was going to be a tax on the self-employed, and then it was abolished.

1112
01:24:21,910 --> 01:24:24,913
[SPEAKER_11]: And then there's this latest u-turn on the dementia tax.

1113
01:24:24,893 --> 01:24:27,641
[SPEAKER_11]: So I'm not one for U-turns.

1114
01:24:27,661 --> 01:24:33,958
[SPEAKER_11]: Plaid Cymru will stick to our manifesto promises and Plaid Cymru will lead for Wales.

1115
01:24:34,921 --> 01:24:35,342
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

1116
01:24:40,385 --> 01:24:43,910
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you to all our speakers for their responses to that final question.

1117
01:24:44,070 --> 01:24:48,076
[SPEAKER_04]: And that brings an end to our audience questions for this evening.

1118
01:24:48,096 --> 01:24:50,980
[SPEAKER_04]: It's time now for our speakers' closing statements.

1119
01:24:51,001 --> 01:24:52,463
[SPEAKER_04]: They are just 30 seconds each.

1120
01:24:52,503 --> 01:24:54,906
[SPEAKER_04]: They've drawn lots for the order of these closing statements.

1121
01:24:55,167 --> 01:25:03,118
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm going to ask our audience here in Cambridge, please applaud right at the end of all seven of the closing statements, because we have a limited time left on air.

1122
01:25:03,539 --> 01:25:07,084
[SPEAKER_04]: And the first of the closing statements comes from Paul Nuttall.

1123
01:25:07,756 --> 01:25:17,385
[SPEAKER_12]: Tonight's been a little bit like Groundhog Day for me because you've heard the same arguments, the same excuses, the same platitudes a hundred times before.

1124
01:25:18,046 --> 01:25:20,689
[SPEAKER_12]: UKIP will always be the outsider in British politics.

1125
01:25:20,729 --> 01:25:26,114
[SPEAKER_12]: It'll be the one that the Westminster elite and the establishment media want to mock and ridicule.

1126
01:25:26,194 --> 01:25:28,036
[SPEAKER_12]: But we have been proven right.

1127
01:25:28,576 --> 01:25:29,738
[SPEAKER_12]: Proven right on Brexit.

1128
01:25:30,238 --> 01:25:31,700
[SPEAKER_12]: Proven right on immigration.

1129
01:25:32,060 --> 01:25:33,762
[SPEAKER_12]: Proven right on grammar schools.

1130
01:25:34,102 --> 01:25:36,244
[SPEAKER_12]: Proven right on protecting our police

1131
01:25:36,224 --> 01:25:37,826
[SPEAKER_12]: and security services.

1132
01:25:38,346 --> 01:25:44,554
[SPEAKER_12]: On June 8th, it's your decision, your country, your vote.

1133
01:25:44,574 --> 01:25:45,034
[SPEAKER_12]: Vote UKIP.

1134
01:25:45,755 --> 01:25:47,677
[SPEAKER_04]: Caroline Lucas, co-leader of the Green Party.

1135
01:25:48,899 --> 01:25:53,764
[SPEAKER_05]: Tonight, this country stands at a crossroads and the choice is stark.

1136
01:25:54,686 --> 01:26:00,312
[SPEAKER_05]: You can stand up for what really matters, values of openness, tolerance and compassion.

1137
01:26:01,313 --> 01:26:05,438
[SPEAKER_05]: Or you can turn inward to isolation, division and hate.

1138
01:26:05,654 --> 01:26:10,721
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, one more MP from the other parties makes no real difference.

1139
01:26:10,741 --> 01:26:13,945
[SPEAKER_05]: But more Green MPs would be truly transformative.

1140
01:26:14,846 --> 01:26:17,790
[SPEAKER_05]: On June the 8th, I urge you, don't look back.

1141
01:26:18,491 --> 01:26:20,814
[SPEAKER_05]: Choose what kind of future you really want.

1142
01:26:21,495 --> 01:26:22,316
[SPEAKER_05]: Vote for change.

1143
01:26:22,877 --> 01:26:23,477
[SPEAKER_05]: Vote Green.

1144
01:26:23,838 --> 01:26:27,403
[SPEAKER_05]: And together, let's build a caring and a more confident Britain.

1145
01:26:28,003 --> 01:26:30,347
[SPEAKER_05]: Jeremy Corbyn.

1146
01:26:30,367 --> 01:26:33,771
[SPEAKER_14]: Tonight, we've seen the real choice facing our country.

1147
01:26:33,920 --> 01:26:37,064
[SPEAKER_14]: between a Labour government and a Conservative government.

1148
01:26:37,845 --> 01:26:53,867
[SPEAKER_14]: This election will decide whether young people are saddled with debt or freed from it, whether we invest in our National Health Service, schools and social care, or they continue to be cut, whether older people get the dignity they deserve or see their incomes fall.

1149
01:26:53,887 --> 01:26:56,471
[SPEAKER_14]: On June the 8th, you have the power to decide.

1150
01:26:56,991 --> 01:27:01,137
[SPEAKER_14]: Vote Labour for the many, not the few.

1151
01:27:01,157 --> 01:27:01,918
[SPEAKER_04]: Angus Robertson.

1152
01:27:03,147 --> 01:27:07,111
[SPEAKER_13]: In this debate, you've heard different views about the kind of country we should be.

1153
01:27:07,792 --> 01:27:17,622
[SPEAKER_13]: For those watching in England, Wales and Northern Ireland, the SNP will always work with others who share our belief in fairness of an outward-looking, welcoming society.

1154
01:27:18,243 --> 01:27:22,027
[SPEAKER_13]: Now more than ever, we need a strong opposition to hold the Tories to account.

1155
01:27:22,768 --> 01:27:31,096
[SPEAKER_13]: The SNP will be that strong voice for Scotland and our pledge is this, to work every day to make Scotland the very best country it can be.

1156
01:27:31,677 --> 01:27:32,698
[SPEAKER_13]: Vote SNP.

1157
01:27:33,522 --> 01:27:34,353
[SPEAKER_11]: Leanne Wood.

1158
01:27:35,378 --> 01:27:41,104
[SPEAKER_11]: Tonight you've heard that Plaid Cymru is the only party putting Wales on the agenda during this election.

1159
01:27:41,725 --> 01:27:45,309
[SPEAKER_11]: But our MPs will play their part for the whole of the UK.

1160
01:27:45,950 --> 01:27:53,438
[SPEAKER_11]: We will stand up for justice and fair play on pensions, on social care and for our cash-starved public services.

1161
01:27:54,099 --> 01:27:58,404
[SPEAKER_11]: So I urge people back home to give us the mandate we need to defend Wales.

1162
01:27:59,005 --> 01:28:00,306
[SPEAKER_11]: Liking us isn't enough.

1163
01:28:00,787 --> 01:28:03,630
[SPEAKER_11]: We need your support and your vote.

1164
01:28:03,610 --> 01:28:07,268
[SPEAKER_11]: Don't let our country be invisible in Westminster.

1165
01:28:07,991 --> 01:28:08,835
[SPEAKER_11]: Vote Plaid.

1166
01:28:09,298 --> 01:28:11,629
[SPEAKER_11]: Vote for Wales.

1167
01:28:12,520 --> 01:28:13,722
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, look, you've heard my arguments.

1168
01:28:14,142 --> 01:28:16,425
[SPEAKER_16]: I'll give you the final say over the Brexit deal.

1169
01:28:16,966 --> 01:28:20,010
[SPEAKER_16]: I will put a penny on income tax for the NHS.

1170
01:28:20,030 --> 01:28:24,757
[SPEAKER_16]: And I will stand up to the Conservatives over the dementia tax and everything else.

1171
01:28:24,777 --> 01:28:25,778
[SPEAKER_16]: Now, Amber Rudd is up next.

1172
01:28:26,239 --> 01:28:27,440
[SPEAKER_16]: She is not the Prime Minister.

1173
01:28:27,781 --> 01:28:29,784
[SPEAKER_16]: The Prime Minister is not here tonight.

1174
01:28:30,364 --> 01:28:31,226
[SPEAKER_16]: She can't be bothered.

1175
01:28:31,626 --> 01:28:32,307
[SPEAKER_16]: So why should you?

1176
01:28:32,708 --> 01:28:35,271
[SPEAKER_16]: In fact, Bake Off is on BBC Two next.

1177
01:28:35,251 --> 01:28:38,236
[SPEAKER_16]: Why not make yourself a brew?

1178
01:28:39,598 --> 01:28:41,501
[SPEAKER_16]: You are not worth Theresa May's time.

1179
01:28:41,882 --> 01:28:43,264
[SPEAKER_16]: Don't give her yours.

1180
01:28:44,325 --> 01:28:46,970
[SPEAKER_04]: And for our final closing statement, Amber Rudd.

1181
01:28:47,010 --> 01:28:48,933
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Tim, for that pass.

1182
01:28:49,674 --> 01:28:53,460
[SPEAKER_06]: So you've heard the squabbling and discord of disagreement here tonight.

1183
01:28:54,462 --> 01:28:56,785
[SPEAKER_06]: You've seen the coalition of chaos in action.

1184
01:28:57,987 --> 01:29:02,254
[SPEAKER_06]: But in the quiet of the polling booth, you have a clear choice.

1185
01:29:02,437 --> 01:29:09,254
[SPEAKER_06]: A vote for anyone other than Theresa May is a vote for Jeremy Corbyn and that coalition.

1186
01:29:09,274 --> 01:29:13,305
[SPEAKER_06]: Our government needs to be at its strongest to take us through Brexit.

1187
01:29:14,187 --> 01:29:17,796
[SPEAKER_06]: It is only Theresa May that can deliver that leadership.

1188
01:29:19,784 --> 01:29:21,526
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, thank you all.

1189
01:29:21,586 --> 01:29:31,858
[SPEAKER_04]: There is going to be live reaction to tonight's debate on the BBC News Channel, and on Friday, Jeremy Corbyn and Theresa May will be taking part in a special edition of Question Time from York.

1190
01:29:32,238 --> 01:29:42,730
[SPEAKER_04]: I'd like to thank all our audience here in Cambridge, especially those whose questions were used tonight, and to all of you watching at home, and indeed to the seven politicians who took part tonight.

1191
01:29:43,251 --> 01:29:45,353
[SPEAKER_04]: From all of us here, goodbye.

